<h2>A3.3 Appeal Window Frustration</h2>

 

<div class="quote-box">

  <div class="quote-header">Dismissal Letter: Appeal Deadline Language</div>

  <div class="quote-label">Reference: E3-APPEAL-LETTER | Date: 13/10/2025 14:06</div>

 

  <div class="quote-label">Verbatim Text</div>

  <div class="quote-verbatim">

    "Any appeal must be submitted in writing within 5 working days of receiving this letter."

  </div>

 

  <div class="quote-metadata">

    <strong>Date/Time:</strong> <span class="timestamp">13/10/2025 14:06</span>

    <br/>

    <strong>Letter Received:</strong> <span class="timestamp">16/10/2025 (3 days later; standard post delivery)</span>

    <br/>

    <strong>Correct Deadline Calculation:</strong> 5 working days from 16/10 = 23/10/2025

  </div>

</div>

 

<div class="quote-box">

  <div class="quote-header">Employer's Deadline Assertion (Incorrect Calculation)</div>

  <div class="quote-label">Reference: E3-APPEAL-EXPIRED | Date: 21/10/2025</div>

 

  <div class="quote-label">Verbatim Text</div>

  <div class="quote-verbatim">

    "The timeframe for submitting a formal appeal expired on 20 October 2025 at 23:59."

  </div>

 

  <div class="quote-metadata">

    <strong>Date/Time:</strong> <span class="timestamp">21/10/2025</span>

    <br/>

    <strong>Employer's Calculation:</strong> 5 working days from 13/10 (send date) = ~20/10

    <br/>

    <strong>Error:</strong> Letter states "OF RECEIVING" - this means receipt date (16/10), not send date (13/10).

    <br/>

    <strong>Claimant's Appeal:</strong> Filed 17/10 - within correct deadline of 23/10

    <br/>

    <strong>Legal Significance:</strong> ACAS Code §4 breach (frustration of appeal right); Procedural unfairness (s.98(4) ERA); Contract interpretation error (bad faith).

  </div>

</div>

 

<h2>A3.4 Summary of Procedural Defects</h2>

 

<p>

  The disciplinary process contained six fundamental ACAS Code breaches, all "unreasonable" and all "consequential" to the dismissal being unfair under ERA s.98(4):

</p>

 

<ol>

  <li><strong>§12-14 Notice breach:</strong> &lt;24 hours given; ACAS minimum 48 hours</li>

  <li><strong>§2 Disclosure breach:</strong> No pre-disclosure of evidence; "at hearing" only</li>

  <li><strong>§6 Impartiality breach:</strong> Chair (Lukasz) was party to dispute; co-chair spouse/co-owner</li>

  <li><strong>§10-15 Health breach:</strong> Fit note disregarded; no adjustments offered</li>

  <li><strong>§6-9 Hearing adequacy breach:</strong> 66-minute hearing for 3+ allegations (predetermination evident)</li>

  <li><strong>§4 Appeal breach:</strong> Deadline miscalculated; appeal right frustrated</li>

</ol>

 

<p>

  Each breach, individually, would be unreasonable. Cumulatively, they establish gross procedural unfairness under ERA s.98(4).

</p>

 

<hr class="page-break"/>

 

