<h2>A5.3 S.26 EqA - Harassment Legal Elements</h2>

 

<p>

  <strong>s.26(1) EqA:</strong> A person (A) harasses another (B) if:

</p>

 

<ol>

  <li><strong>A engages in unwanted conduct:</strong> Vulgarity, dehumanisation, isolation, humiliation, intimidation - all documented</li>

  <li><strong>Related to a protected characteristic:</strong> Stress (disability manifestation); or more broadly, human dignity (applies to all)</li>

  <li><strong>Purpose or effect:</strong> Violating B's dignity OR creating an intimidating/hostile/degrading environment</li>

  <li><strong>Taking into account B's perception, circumstances, etc:</strong> ADHD individual with known stress sensitivity; employer knew of GP referral</li>

</ol>

 

<p>

  <strong>Application:</strong> All four elements satisfied. Conduct documented; effect was violating dignity and creating hostile environment; Claimant's circumstances (ADHD, stress) known to employer.

</p>

 

<h2>A5.4 Relief Sought (A5)</h2>

 

<ol>

  <li><strong>Declaration:</strong> Employer harassed Claimant contrary to EqA 2010 s.26.</li>

  <li><strong>Compensation:</strong> Separate Vento award (harassment - not discrimination-based).</li>

  <li><strong>Aggravated damages:</strong> For post-dismissal continuation of harassment (threats, intimidation).</li>

  <li><strong>Statutory interest:</strong> 8% per annum from date of conduct (Feb 2025 onwards).</li>

</ol>

 

<hr class="page-break"/>

 

<h1>A6: Unfair Dismissal &amp; Financial Motive (s.98(4) ERA; s.104 ERA)</h1>

 

<h2>A6.1 Moving the Goalposts - Operative Standard Shift</h2>

 

<p>

  <strong>Critical Pivot: From "COVER" to "AUTHORISATION"</strong>

</p>

 

<h3>Stage 1: Operative Standard Before 11/10 = "COVER"</h3>

 

<div class="quote-box">

  <div class="quote-header">Claimant's Email (15:29): Confirming Cover Arrangement</div>

  <div class="quote-label">Reference: E6-COVER-001 | Date: 11/10/2025 15:29</div>

 

  <div class="quote-label">Verbatim Text</div>

  <div class="quote-verbatim">

    "I started work today at 11:40 and plan to leave at approximately 16:30, not before Anastasia arrives to take over the shift. Before leaving, I did everything I could to organise proper cover. As requested, I have left the company laptop on the premises."

  </div>

 

  <div class="quote-metadata">

    <strong>Date/Time:</strong> <span class="timestamp">11/10/2025 15:29</span>

    <br/>

    <strong>Analysis:</strong> Claimant explicitly states: (1) Waiting for Anastasia's arrival. (2) "Did everything I could to organise proper cover." (3) Operations continuity maintained (laptop on premises).

    <br/>

    <strong>Operative Standard:</strong> Performance of duty to provide "cover" (shift continuity). This standard is MET.

  </div>

</div>

 

<h3>Stage 2: Pivot Moment - New Rule "AUTHORISATION" Introduced (15:38)</h3>

 

<div class="quote-box">

  <div class="quote-header">Employer's Response: Introduction of "Authorisation" Requirement</div>

  <div class="quote-label">Reference: E6-PIVOT-001 | Date: 11/10/2025 15:38</div>

 

  <div class="quote-label">Verbatim Text</div>

  <div class="quote-verbatim">

    "this was not authorised in advance. I organised the shift cover myself to ensure continuity of operations - not you."

  </div>

 

  <div class="quote-metadata">

    <strong>Date/Time:</strong> <span class="timestamp">11/10/2025 15:38 (9 minutes after Claimant's email)</span>

    <br/>

    <strong>Analysis:</strong> FIRST use of word "authorised" in response. Novel rule introduced. Operative standard shifts from "cover" (which was arranged) to "authorisation" (which was never a stated requirement).

    <br/>

    <strong>Critical Issue:</strong> Employment contract (CP-01) reviewed - CONTAINS NO "AUTHORISATION" REQUIREMENT. No policy document cited requiring advance approval.

    <br/>

    <strong>Moving Goalposts:</strong> Employer retroactively applies novel standard to conduct already evaluated under different standard.

  </div>

</div>

 

<h2>A6.2 Misstatement of Law (ERA s.57A)</h2>

 

<div class="quote-box">

  <div class="quote-header">Employer's False Legal Assertion</div>

  <div class="quote-label">Reference: E6-LAW-FALSE | Date: 11/10/2025 16:05-16:08</div>

 

  <div class="quote-label">Verbatim Text</div>

  <div class="quote-verbatim">

    "Emergencies involving friends are not covered under UK employment law for time off for dependants. Please bring the company card back to the restaurant and leave it in a secure place today."

  </div>

 

  <div class="quote-metadata">

    <strong>Date/Time:</strong> <span class="timestamp">11/10/2025 16:05-16:08</span>

    <br/>

    <strong>Legal Fact - ERA 1996 s.57A(1):</strong> Employee has right to reasonable time off for dependant if:

    <br/>

    "(a) a spouse, child or parent of the employee, or

    <br/>

    (b) a person who reasonably relies on the employee for care."

    <br/>

    <strong>Application to Marek Piszczek:</strong>

    <ul style="margin: 6pt 0pt; padding-left: 18pt;">

      <li>No family in UK (thus reasonably relies on Claimant)</li>

      <li>Years of close relationship established</li>

      <li>Medical emergency (hospital transport) is urgent care situation</li>

      <li>QUALIFIES under s.57A(1)(b) "person who reasonably relies on employee for care"</li>

    </ul>

    <br/>

    <strong>Employer's Assertion:</strong> FALSE - Contradicted by statute

    <br/>

    <strong>Legal Significance:</strong> Misstatement of law is evidence of bad faith and pretextual basis for dismissal.

  </div>

</div>

 

<h2>A6.3 Financial Motive for Dismissal</h2>

 

<div class="quote-box">

  <div class="quote-header">Employer's Cash-Flow Crisis Disclosure</div>

  <div class="quote-label">Reference: E6-MOTIVE-001 | Date: 03/10/2025 12:58</div>

 

  <div class="quote-label">Verbatim Text (Original - Polish)</div>

  <div class="quote-verbatim">

    "Po prostu nie mam pieni_dzy na po_ow_ wyp_at i wasze sk_adki, rozumiesz?"

  </div>

 

  <div class="quote-label">Translation (English)</div>

  <div class="quote-translation">

    "I simply don't have money for half the wages and your contributions, do you understand?"

  </div>

 

  <div class="quote-metadata">

    <strong>Date/Time:</strong> <span class="timestamp">03/10/2025 12:58 (10 days BEFORE dismissal on 13/10)</span>

    <br/>

    <strong>Context:</strong> Employer explicitly discloses financial crisis. Cannot fund "half the wages" - implies significant staff reduction needed.

    <br/>

    <strong>Claimant's Salary:</strong> GBP 2,800/month (highest senior staff member identified)

    <br/>

    <strong>Timeline:</strong> Financial crisis disclosed 10 days before dismissal of senior manager

    <br/>

    <strong>Inference:</strong> Dismissal appears motivated by cost-cutting (payroll reduction), not the stated reason.

    <br/>

    <strong>Legal Significance:</strong> Evidence of financial motive undermines credibility of disciplinary reason; suggests dismissal unfair under s.98(4) ERA (reason not genuine or pretext).

  </div>

</div>

 

<h2>A6.4 S.98(4) ERA - Three-Part Fairness Test</h2>

 

<p>

  <strong>Test Under ERA 1996 s.98(4):</strong> Dismissal is fair only if:

</p>

 

<ol>

  <li><strong>Fair reason shown:</strong> One of the statutory reasons (capability, conduct, redundancy, statutory illegality, SOSR, etc.)</li>

  <li><strong>Procedurally fair:</strong> Following ACAS Code and natural justice</li>

  <li><strong>Reasonable in circumstances:</strong> Overall proportionate response</li>

</ol>

 

<p>

  <strong>Application to This Case:</strong>

</p>

 

<h3>Reason Given: "Leaving without authorisation" + "misrepresentation" + "failure to return card"</h3>

 

<p>

  <strong>Issue 1: Is the reason genuine/true?</strong>

</p>

 

<ul>

  <li><strong>"Leaving without authorisation":</strong> Novel requirement introduced retroactively. Employment contract silent on "authorisation" requirement. Operative standard was "cover" (which was arranged).</li>

  <li><strong>"Misrepresentation":</strong> Claimant stated he "organised proper cover" - this is TRUE. Anastasia confirmed attendance. Employer's claim he "organised cover himself" is contradicted by evidence.</li>

  <li><strong>"Failure to return card":</strong> Card kept during emergency (Claimant left at 16:30, returned same day). No substantive issue.</li>

  <li><strong>Underlying law misstatement:</strong> Employer falsely stated s.57A does not cover friends. This is incorrect law.</li>

</ul>

 

<p>

  <strong>Conclusion on Reason: NOT genuine. Reason is pretext.</strong>

</p>

 

<h3>Issue 2: Procedural Fairness?</h3>

 

<p>

  Six ACAS Code breaches documented (see A3 section above). Process was fundamentally unfair.

</p>

 

<p>

  <strong>Conclusion on Procedure: Massively unfair.</strong>

</p>

 

<h3>Issue 3: Reasonable in circumstances?</h3>

 

<p>

  Dismissal of 9-month employee for arranging shift cover during medical emergency. No alternatives considered (warning, suspension, investigation). Financial motive evident (cash-flow crisis disclosed days before).

</p>

 

<p>

  <strong>Conclusion on Reasonableness: Unreasonable.</strong>

</p>

 

<h2>A6.5 S.104 ERA - Automatic Unfairness (Alternative Basis)</h2>

 

<p>

  <strong>ERA 1996 s.104:</strong> An employee is automatically unfairly dismissed if the reason (or principal reason) is that the employee asserted a statutory right (including ERA s.57A right to time off for dependants).

</p>

 

<p>

  <strong>Application:</strong> If Claimant's dismissal reason included (even partially) assertion of s.57A right (time off for medical dependant care), dismissal is automatically unfair under s.104. No procedural fairness defence available; no "contributory conduct" reduction applies.

</p>

 

<p>

  <strong>Evidence of s.104 Trigger:</strong> Employer's email (16:05) explicitly references s.57A ("Emergencies involving friends are not covered under UK employment law for time off for dependants"). By mischaracterizing s.57A, employer signals that assertion of s.57A right was a factor in dismissal decision.

</p>

 

<h2>A6.6 Relief Sought (A6)</h2>

 

<ol>

  <li><strong>Declaration:</strong> Dismissal was unfair under ERA 1996 s.98(4) (reason not genuine, procedure unfair, unreasonable in circumstances).</li>

  <li><strong>Declaration (Alternative):</strong> Dismissal was automatically unfair under ERA 1996 s.104 (assertion of s.57A statutory right).</li>

  <li><strong>Compensation:</strong> Compensatory award for unfair dismissal (see A7-A10).</li>

  <li><strong>No contributory conduct deduction:</strong> Under s.104 automatic unfairness, such reduction does not apply.</li>

  <li><strong>ACAS uplift:</strong> 25% uplift under s.207A TULRCA (six core ACAS Code breaches; all consequential).</li>

</ol>

 

