<h1>A11: Breach of Contract (Express &amp; Implied Terms; s.57A ERA)</h1>

 

<h2>A11.1 Express Term Breach - "Authorisation" Requirement</h2>

 

<h3>Employment Contract (CP-01) Review</h3>

 

<div class="quote-box">

  <div class="quote-header">Contract Provision: Time Off &amp; Leave</div>

  <div class="quote-label">Reference: CP-01-TIMEOFF | Section: 4 (Leave &amp; Time Off)</div>

 

  <div class="quote-label">Finding</div>

  <div class="quote-verbatim">

    Employment Contract reviewed: DOES NOT CONTAIN any clause requiring "advance authorisation" for time off. DOES NOT CONTAIN any clause requiring "manager approval" for departures. DOES NOT REFERENCE "written permission" requirement.

  </div>

 

  <div class="quote-metadata">

    <strong>Operative Standard in Contract:</strong> Cover/continuity of service (implied). No "authorisation" requirement specified.

    <br/>

    <strong>Breach:</strong> Employer introduces "authorisation" requirement (11/10/2025, 15:38) retroactively, without contractual basis.

    <br/>

    <strong>Legal Significance:</strong> Breach of contract (modification of operative standard without agreement); Bad faith (moving goalposts).

  </div>

</div>

 

<h2>A11.2 Implied Term Breach - Mutual Trust &amp; Confidence</h2>

 

<p>

  <strong>Implied term in all employment contracts:</strong> Mutual trust and confidence (Robertson v British Gas plc [1983] ICR 351).

</p>

 

<p>

  <strong>Standard:</strong> Employer must not, without reasonable and proper cause, conduct itself in a manner calculated and likely to destroy or seriously damage the relationship of confidence and trust between employer and employee.

</p>

 

<h3>Evidence of Breach (February - October 2025)</h3>

 

<table>

  <thead>

    <tr>

      <th>Conduct</th>

      <th>Date</th>

      <th>Breach Type</th>

    </tr>

  </thead>

  <tbody>

    <tr>

      <td>Vulgar management ("don't f***ing enter")</td>

      <td>05/02/2025</td>

      <td>Disrespect; dehumanization</td>

    </tr>

    <tr>

      <td>"Control people like robots; you become robot too"</td>

      <td>05/02/2025</td>

      <td>Dehumanization; violation of dignity</td>

    </tr>

    <tr>

      <td>Micromanagement with coercive threat (card removal)</td>

      <td>29/08/2025</td>

      <td>Coercion; intimidation; distrust</td>

    </tr>

    <tr>

      <td>Predetermination ("trust already gone")</td>

      <td>10/10/2025</td>

      <td>Prejudgment; destruction of trust</td>

    </tr>

    <tr>

      <td>Public isolation ("don't message Nikodem")</td>

      <td>10/10/2025</td>

      <td>Isolation; humiliation; distrust</td>

    </tr>

    <tr>

      <td>Rushes through unfair disciplinary (66 min)</td>

      <td>13/10/2025</td>

      <td>Disrespect; lack of fairness</td>

    </tr>

    <tr>

      <td>Public humiliation (WhatsApp announcement)</td>

      <td>13/10/2025</td>

      <td>Violation of dignity; disrespect</td>

    </tr>

    <tr>

      <td>Post-dismissal legal threats; intimidation</td>

      <td>14-17/10/2025</td>

      <td>Coercion; harassment; bad faith</td>

    </tr>

    <tr>

      <td>Misstatement of law (s.57A)</td>

      <td>11/10/2025</td>

      <td>Bad faith; dishonesty</td>

    </tr>

  </tbody>

</table>

 

<p>

  <strong>Cumulative Effect:</strong> The pattern of conduct (vulgarity, dehumanization, micromanagement, coercion, predetermination, humiliation, intimidation) is calculated and likely to destroy the trust and confidence between employer and employee.

</p>

 

<p>

  <strong>Conclusion:</strong> Fundamental breach of implied term of mutual trust and confidence.

</p>

 

<h2>A11.3 S.57A ERA - Time Off for Dependants (Protected Right)</h2>

 

<p>

  <strong>ERA 1996 s.57A(1):</strong> An employee has the right to take a reasonable amount of time off work during normal working hours in order to deal with:

</p>

 

<ol>

  <li>The unexpected or sudden illness of a person who depends on the employee for care</li>

  <li>The unexpected breakdown of arrangements for the care of a person who depends on the employee</li>

  <li>The unexpected occurrence of an incident involving a child of the employee, where the child is attending school or other educational establishment</li>

  <li>To provide assistance on an occasion when a person who depends on the employee for care is injured or assaulted</li>

  <li>In connection with the death of a person who depends on the employee for care</li>

  <li>To deal with matters arising from the employee's relationship with a spouse, civil partner or person of marrital status</li>

</ol>

 

<p>

  <strong>"Dependent" defined (s.57A(2)):</strong>

</p>

 

<blockquote style="border-left: 2pt solid #0b3f5c; padding: 8pt 10pt; margin: 8pt 0pt; font-size: 10pt;">

"(a) a spouse, child or parent of the employee, or (b) a person who reasonably relies on the employee for care"

</blockquote>

 

<h3>Application: Marek Piszczek as "Dependent"</h3>

 

<p>

  <strong>Facts:</strong>

</p>

 

<ul>

  <li><strong>Marek Piszczek:</strong> Close friend; no family in UK; medical emergency (hospital transport required)</li>

  <li><strong>Reasonable reliance:</strong> Called Claimant during emergency; Claimant organized transport; years of established relationship</li>

  <li><strong>Sudden medical event:</strong> Hospital admission = "unexpected or sudden illness" (s.57A(1)(a) context)</li>

  <li><strong>Incident response:</strong> Transport during medical crisis = "to provide assistance on an occasion when person depends on employee for care" (s.57A(1)(d))</li>

</ul>

 

<p>

  <strong>Conclusion:</strong> Marek Piszczek qualifies as "person who reasonably relies on the employee for care" under s.57A(2)(b). Claimant's time off is PROTECTED under statute.

</p>

 

<h2>A11.4 S.104 ERA - Automatic Unfairness (If Dismissal Related to s.57A)</h2>

 

<p>

  <strong>ERA 1996 s.104:</strong> An employee shall be regarded as unfairly dismissed if the reason (or, if there is more than one, the principal reason) for the dismissal is that the employee asserted a statutory right.

</p>

 

<p>

  <strong>Statutory right includes:</strong> Right to reasonable time off for dependant (s.57A).

</p>

 

<p>

  <strong>Application:</strong> If Claimant's dismissal reason included (even partially) assertion of s.57A right, dismissal is automatically unfair under s.104. No procedural fairness defence; no "contributory conduct" reduction applies.

</p>

 

<p>

  <strong>Evidence of s.104 Trigger:</strong> Employer's email (16:05, 11/10) explicitly references dependant law: "Emergencies involving friends are not covered under UK employment law for time off for dependants." By asserting false law, employer signals that s.57A right was a factor in dismissal.

</p>

 

<h2>A11.5 Relief Sought (A11)</h2>

 

<ol>

  <li><strong>Declaration:</strong> Employment contract did NOT contain "authorisation" requirement; employer breached express term by retroactively applying novel standard.</li>

  <li><strong>Declaration:</strong> Employer breached implied term of mutual trust and confidence through pattern of vulgarity, dehumanization, coercion, and predetermination.</li>

  <li><strong>Declaration:</strong> Claimant's time off on 11/10 was protected under ERA s.57A (time off for dependant).</li>

  <li><strong>Declaration (Alternative):</strong> Dismissal was automatically unfair under ERA s.104 (assertion of s.57A statutory right).</li>

  <li><strong>Compensation:</strong> Damages for breach of contract (implied term breach): GBP 2,000 - GBP 5,000.</li>

  <li><strong>Statutory interest:</strong> 8% per annum from date of breach (13/10/2025 dismissal).</li>

</ol>

 

